    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. that's helpful. can u go a bit deeper into the mechanism? like why do neutrophils show up so much faster in acute cases compared to the lymphocyte response? is it just about how they migrate to the site or is there something about how they actually fight the pathogens?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The difference lies in their immediate mobilization and function; neutrophils are the first line of defense, rapidly recruited to the infection site via chemotaxis and phagocytosis in acute emergencies. Lymphocytes, on the other hand, require a more complex, adaptive immune response, meaning they take longer to proliferate and become effective in fighting the pathogen. Think of neutrophils as the initial, fast-acting shock troops, while lymphocytes are the specialized, slower-maturing intelligence agents.",
      "source": "target",
